Preheat your #oven{} to 180°C. Pop the @butternut squash{200%g}(diced) on a lined #baking tray{} and drizzle with @olive oil{2%tbsp}, @salt{} and @black pepper{}. Toss to coat, spread out and roast on the top shelf of your oven, ~{30-35%minutes}.

Meanwhile, cut the @cherry plum tomatoes{200%g} in half and pop into a #small bowl{}. Peel and grate the @garlic{1%clove} (or use a #garlic press{}). Stir into the tomatoes along with the @red wine vinegar{6%tbsp}, @?sugar{¼%tsp} (if using), a pinch of @salt{} and @black pepper{} and a drizzle of @olive oil{}. Set aside.

When the butternut squash has been in the oven for ~{10%minutes}, remove the tray from the oven. Give the squash a good toss and push it to one side of the tray. Pop the tomatoes on the other side of the tray. Return to the oven to cook for the remaining ~{20-25%minutes}, until the squash is golden and tomatoes are beginning to colour and burst.

In the meantime, heat a generous splash of @olive oil{} in #small frying pan{} over medium-low heat. Halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1} and add to the pan with a pinch of @salt{}. Slowly cook the onion, stirring occasionally, until soft and beginning to colour, ~{8-10%minutes}. While the onion is cooking, make the pesto and pop your #kettle{} on to boil for the pasta.

== Walnut Pesto ==

Pick the @basil{12%leaves} leaves from their stalks and finely chop (discard the stalks). Finely chop the @chives{1%tsp} and the @hazelnuts{20%g}. Zest the @lemon{½}(zested) then cut in half.

In a small bowl, mix together the basil, chives, walnuts, three-quarters of the @grated hard Italian style cheese{40%g}, half the lemon zest, the @water{1%tbsp}. Season to taste with a squeeze of lemon juice and a pinch of @salt{} and @black pepper{}.

> The pesto brings a really lovely layer of texture from the walnutty flavour.

== Pasta and Assembly ==

Pour the water from the kettle into a #large saucepan{}. Bring back to the boil and add a pinch of @salt{}. Add the @fusilli{160%g} and cook until al dente, around ~{9%minutes}.

> 'Al dente' simply means the pasta is cooked through but has a tiny bit of firmness left in the middle.

Once cooked, drain in a #colander{}. Return to the pan (off the heat) and drizzle with a little @olive oil{} to stop it sticking.

Once everything is cooked, stir the pesto, onion and @crème fraîche{75%g} into the pasta. Gently mix in the roasted tomatoes, butternut squash and any roasting juices from the pan. Season to taste with more lemon juice, salt and pepper if needed. Finally, stir in the @wild rocket{20%g}. Divide between your plates and sprinkle over the remaining cheese. Enjoy!